<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="utf-8">
<title>{{ .OrgName }} — AI Impact Report</title>
<link rel="stylesheet" href="assets/reveal.css">
<link rel="stylesheet" href="assets/theme/white.css">
<style>
  .reveal h1, .reveal h2, .reveal h3 { text-transform: none; }
  .reveal .big-number {
    font-size: 4em;
    font-weight: 700;
    line-height: 1;
    margin: 0.1em 0 0.2em 0;
  }
  .reveal .big-number-grid {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-around;
    align-items: flex-start;
    gap: 2em;
    margin: 1.5em 0;
  }
  .reveal .big-number-grid > div { text-align: center; max-width: 280px; }
  .reveal .footnote { font-size: 0.55em; color: #666; margin-top: 1em; }
  .reveal .caveats { font-size: 0.7em; }
  .reveal .chart {
    width: 90%;
    height: 70vh;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
</style>
</head>
<body>
<div class="reveal">
<div class="slides">

<section>
  <h1>AI Impact Report</h1>
  <h3>{{ .OrgName }}</h3>
  <p>Week of {{ .ReportDate.Format "January 2, 2006" }}</p>
  <p class="footnote">Scope: {{ .Scope }} &middot; Window: {{ .WindowStart.Format "Jan 02, 2006" }} – {{ .WindowEnd.Format "Jan 02, 2006" }}</p>
  <aside class="notes">
    Loupe baseline report. Local-only — no data left this machine. Skeptic mode: the methodology slide at the end lists what we measured and how.
  </aside>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Adoption</h2>
  <div class="big-number-grid">
    <div>
      <p class="big-number">{{ .TotalCommits }}</p>
      <p>commits over {{ len .Weeks }} weeks</p>
    </div>
    <div>
      <p class="big-number">{{ printf "%.1f%%" .AICommitPct }}</p>
      <p>of commits carry an AI co-author trailer</p>
    </div>
    <div>
      <p class="big-number">{{ .AIAuthorCount }}/{{ .DistinctAuthorCount }}</p>
      <p>devs with at least one AI-tagged commit</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p class="footnote">{{ .CutoverText }}</p>
  <aside class="notes">
    Trailer-based detection is conservative: Claude and Aider write Co-Authored-By trailers by default; Cursor and Copilot generally don't. Real adoption among Cursor/Copilot users is likely higher than this chart shows.
  </aside>
</section>

<section data-chart="throughput">
  <h2>Weekly throughput</h2>
  <div id="throughput-chart" class="chart"></div>
  <aside class="notes">
    Commits per week, stacked human vs AI-tagged. Merge commits included. A truncated rightmost bar usually reflects a partial week at report time.
  </aside>
</section>

<section data-chart="adoption">
  <h2>Adoption over time</h2>
  <div id="adoption-chart" class="chart"></div>
  <aside class="notes">
    Percentage of active devs per week with at least one AI-tagged commit. The shape of this curve matters more than any single point — board-friendly chart.
  </aside>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Methodology &amp; caveats</h2>
  <div class="caveats" style="text-align: left;">
    <h4>How AI signals are detected</h4>
    <ul>
      <li><b>High confidence</b> — <code>Co-Authored-By</code> trailer from Claude / Claude Code, Aider, Copilot, Cursor</li>
      <li><b>Medium</b> — seat-holder + timing patterns (not yet implemented)</li>
      <li><b>Low</b> — commit-shape heuristics (not used in this report)</li>
    </ul>
    <h4>Not in this report yet</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Cycle time (needs Jira tickets + Bitbucket PRs)</li>
      <li>Defect rate / quality counterweight</li>
      <li>Per-team breakdown</li>
    </ul>
    <p><b>Cutover:</b> {{ .CutoverText }}</p>
    <p><b>Threshold:</b> a week qualifies as the cutover when AI-tagged commits reach {{ printf "%.0f%%" .CutoverThresholdPct }} of weekly commits.</p>
  </div>
  <aside class="notes">
    ROI is intentionally omitted — the assumption it requires (hours saved per AI-tagged commit) can't be defended in front of a skeptical CFO.
  </aside>
</section>

</div>
</div>
<script src="assets/reveal.js"></script>
<script src="assets/echarts.min.js"></script>
<script>
  // Option payloads emitted by internal/deck/charts.go. They are JSON
  // object literals — html/template's contextual escaper marks them as
  // template.JS so they embed verbatim here.
  const throughputOption = {{ .Charts.ThroughputJSON }};
  const adoptionOption = {{ .Charts.AdoptionJSON }};

  // Initialise reveal first. reveal hides slides via display:none, so
  // ECharts measures 0x0 on hidden containers — we re-size each chart on
  // every slidechanged event so it lays out correctly when its slide
  // becomes visible.
  Reveal.initialize({
    hash: true,
    controls: true,
    progress: true,
    slideNumber: 'c/t',
    transition: 'fade'
  }).then(function () {
    const throughput = echarts.init(document.getElementById('throughput-chart'));
    throughput.setOption(throughputOption);
    const adoption = echarts.init(document.getElementById('adoption-chart'));
    adoption.setOption(adoptionOption);

    function resizeAll() { throughput.resize(); adoption.resize(); }
    Reveal.on('slidechanged', resizeAll);
    window.addEventListener('resize', resizeAll);
    // Initial sizing for whichever slide is current.
    setTimeout(resizeAll, 0);
  });
</script>
</body>
</html>
